```
public class PowerOfThree {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        return (Math.log10(n) / Math.log10(3) - (int) (Math.log10(n) / Math.log10(3))) == 0;
    }
}
```
The solution first checks if the input number is less than or equal to zero, and returns false if it is. Otherwise, it calculates the logarithm base 10 of the input number and divides it by the logarithm base 10 of 3 to get the exponent of 3 that would result in the input number. The solution then checks if this exponent is an integer value by subtracting the integer part of the exponent from the exponent itself and checking if the result is equal to zero. If the result is zero, then the exponent is an integer and the input number is a power of three. Otherwise, the input number is not a power of three.

Note that this solution assumes that the input number is an integer. If the input number is a floating-point number, then the logarithm calculation may not be accurate enough to determine if the exponent is an integer. In that case, a different approach would be needed to solve the problem.

